sorry--got ot. Here's what Einstein himself said about his beliefs and religion, &quot;A man's ethical behavior should be based effectually on sympathy, education, and social ties and needs; no religious basis is necessary. Man would indeed be in a poor way if he had to be restrained by fear of punishment and hopes of reward after death.&quot; He sort of saw pursuing the nature of the universe and the deep feeling of satisfaction this gave to great intellects a &quot;cosmic religious&quot; feeling that could be interpreted as religious in the same way people use the phrase &quot;religious experience&quot; to describe watching Randy Moss in action or have an &quot;epiphany&quot; that the Vikings are the best football team...<br>
<br>
